Do I detect the SGML evangelists in full cry in the current crop of posts?
From what I've seen SGML requires a fair amount of up-front work to set up
a document. This (costly) work is justified if you want to re-use a
document in different formats - although you might need several re-uses to
justify the effort. 
Using the PDFWriter I can go from an (existing) Word document, link from
its (existing) table of contents to the relevant pages, creating bookmarks
en route, and link to a couple of other documents, ending up with a
multi-platform linked file, in literally a few minutes. 
I'm not claiming that the current implementation of Acrobat is all I'd
wish for, but it provides a quick cost-effective means of getting
documents on-line.

Horses for courses?

I'm not going to follow-up on the related threads, but the sniffy comments
I've seen seem to suggest that SGML 'purists' are joyously latching on to
badly prepared documents as an excuse to bash Acrobat.

