Claude L. Bullard <bullardc@source.asset.com> wrote:
>Any thoughts out there on the announcement at Seybold that Adobe and IBM
>and Netscape have a deal for making Acrobat (a PDF player) a new standard
>for the WWW?  Given the moves in NIST to create a FIPS for PDF and the
>money being allocated to convert millions of Federal documents into PDF,
>this appears to be an important development that could deal a crippling
>blow to HTML apps.  Before anyone gets hot, consider that a hypothesis
>based on the capabilities of both to represent book metaphors.
>
>While it may not be sunny news to HTML, it may the best thing to happen to
>SGML since the WWW began.

Hmm... my impression is the exact opposite.

It's good news for HTML; widespread acceptance
of PDF may relieve some of the pressure to turn HTML
into a page formatting language and leave it room
to evolve in a direction consistent with its original
goal as a simple, platform-independant, content-based 
hypertext markup language.  When Joe Homepage asks
"How do I make my text show up in 11pt Gorgonzola Italic
and wrap it around this triangle-shaped bitmapped graphic?"
the HTML community will be able to say "Use PDF!"
and there will be less temptation to invent a 
<TRIANGLE-SHAPED-BITMAP> element.

On the other hand, it's bad news for SGML as a whole.
HTML, for all its flaws, has dramatically increased
SGML's visibility among the thousands eager to jump
onto "this new Information SuperHighway thing".   A
few -- not many, but a few -- have even caught on to
the idea of generic markup, and *like* it.  If PDF really
takes off, there is a great danger that HTML will simply
be ignored; established webheads will tell newcomers
"Oh, don't bother with that, it's worthless; it can't
even wrap text around triangle-shaped bitmaps!"  And 
as long as their documents Look Good Under Netscape (tm),
they'll never know what they're missing.


